8/10/25, 19:11 - +91 75260 80521: Here is a typical syllabus for a Managerial Economics course, as commonly offered at university level:
Managerial Economics Syllabus Overview
Unit I: Nature and Scope of Managerial Economics
	‚Ä¢	Definition, objectives, and importance of managerial economics
	‚Ä¢	Fundamental economic concepts: Opportunity cost, discounting, time perspective, marginalism, equi-marginal concept
	‚Ä¢	Relationship with other disciplines (micro and macroeconomics)
	‚Ä¢	Role of managerial economics in decision making and firm objectives
Unit II: Demand and Supply Analysis
	‚Ä¢	Market demand and supply functions and curves
	‚Ä¢	Law of demand, elasticity of demand and supply
	‚Ä¢	Consumer behavior theories (cardinal and ordinal approaches)
	‚Ä¢	Demand forecasting: Methods, significance, and application in business decisions
Unit III: Production and Cost Analysis
	‚Ä¢	Theory of production: Factors of production, law of variable proportions, returns to scale
	‚Ä¢	Production functions: Cobb-Douglas and CES
	‚Ä¢	Cost concepts: Short-run and long-run cost curves, cost estimation, cost-output relationship
	‚Ä¢	Economies and diseconomies of scale
Unit IV: Market Structures and Pricing Practices
	‚Ä¢	Different market structures: Perfect competition, monopoly, monopolistic competition, oligopoly, duopoly
	‚Ä¢	Price determination and price discrimination, product pricing methods
	‚Ä¢	Game theory and competitive strategies
Unit V: Profit Analysis and Business Cycles
	‚Ä¢	Theories and concepts of profit: Profit maximization, alternative firm objectives
	‚Ä¢	Break-even analysis and its managerial uses
	‚Ä¢	National income: Concepts, measurement, and significance
	‚Ä¢	Business cycles: Meaning, phases, causes, and strategies for management
Supplementary Topics (varies by university)
	‚Ä¢	Government intervention and regulation, public utility regulation
	‚Ä¢	Risk, uncertainty, and decision making
	‚Ä¢	Innovation, technology, and firm competitiveness
	‚Ä¢	Case studies on decision making and applications of managerial economics.
This structure ensures that students understand not only economic theory but also how to apply it to real-world business decisions, making the course both analytical and practical.

8/27/25, 18:04 - +91 62002 35878: There is no need to visit for Bonafide apply. From Aug end when candidate received *Roll No and IITP E-mail ID* and he had submitted the hard copy of admission document, candidate can apply through mail also by sending mail on moodle_support@iitp.ac.in only by their Institute (Issued by IIT Patna) mail ID. 
*Below is the Process for Bonafide certificate request:*

‚Ä¢	Fill Up Application Form  
‚Ä¢	Soft/Scan copy of Aadhar Card
‚Ä¢	Soft/Scan copy of IIT-Patna Identity Card
‚Ä¢	Fee Payment Receipt
‚Ä¢	Payment receipt screenshot (Academic Service Charges) of the payment confirmation along with the reference number

Pay the applicable academic service charges (Rs. 150/- for Bonafide) on attached UPI Scanner. 

After Signed by Signing Authority, Scan copy will be share on Mail and Hard copy to collect from 301-A, Academics Department,3rd Floor Admin Block,
IIT Patna, Kanpa Road, Bihta, Patna ‚Äì 801106, India

We will forward it to the competent authorities. After submitting all the required details, please allow 1-2 working weeks for processing.

8/30/25, 21:55 - +91 94178 36823: <Media omitted>
8/30/25, 22:01 - +91 94178 36823: Computer uses IEEE Floating Point representation to store those numbers which we usually call decimal numbers in our language. You see we humans can see the point and mark the number as integer or decimal but there's no concept of decimal point in computer's storage. So it uses a sort of exponential form to store such numbers.

Since computer understands only 0 and 1 therefore the base used is two for storing the numbers in the exponent as well. Then there are a ton of steps to be performed in chronology to convert the decimal number into IEEE FP representation number which would be obviously be in binary as its the last thing after translation that the computer would understand. 

So this is the basic fundamental. 0.1 is different for storing exactly due to the reason mentioned in this image. I hope now there's some clarity on this ambiguity? @‚Å®+91 62028 94491‚Å© <This message was edited>

org = "indian institute of technology patna"
print("Original String:", org)
print("Using title():", org.title())
print("Using capitalize():", org.capitalize())

print("\n" + "-"*50 + "\n")

# 2. Bill calculation with discount
p = 120       # price per item
q = 5         # quantity
d = 50        # discount

bill = p * q
final_bill = bill - d
avg_price = final_bill / q

print("Total Bill (before discount):", bill)
print("Discount:", d)
print("Final Bill (to pay):", final_bill)
print("Average Price per Item:", avg_price)

print("\n" + "-"*50 + "\n")

# 3. Swap two numbers without third variable
a = 10
b = 20
print("Before Swap: a =", a, "b =", b)

a = a + b
b = a - b
a = a - b

print("After Swap: a =", a, "b =", b)

print("\n" + "-"*50 + "\n")

# 4. Wallet Balance Updates
balance = 0
print("Initial Balance:", balance)

S = 5000  # stipend
M = 2000  # mess bill
C = 200   # cashback
T = 500   # travel

balance += S
print("After Stipend:", balance)

balance -= M
print("After Paying Mess Bill:", balance)

balance += C
print("After Cashback:", balance)

balance -= T
print("After Travel:", balance)

total_expenditure = M + T
savings = balance

print("Total Expenditure:", total_expenditure)
print("Savings:", savings)
print("Final Balance:", balance)

print("\n" + "-"*50 + "\n")

# 5. Student Exam Journey (Weighted Score Calculation)
quiz1 = 8      # out of 10
quiz2 = 7      # out of 10
midsem = 60    # out of 100
endsem = 120   # out of 200

# Normalize marks to percentage, then multiply by weights
final_score = (
    (quiz1 / 10) * 10 +
    (quiz2 / 10) * 10 +
    (midsem / 100) * 30 +
    (endsem / 200) * 50
)

print("Final Score (out of 100):", final_score)

9/6/25, 20:06 - +91 90064 21115: # 1. Swap Two Numbers Without Using Third Variable (using Bitwise XOR)
a = 15
b = 25
print("Before Swap: a =", a, "b =", b)

a = a ^ b
b = a ^ b
a = a ^ b

print("After Swap: a =", a, "b =", b)

print("\n" + "-"*50 + "\n")

# 2. Check if given integer is odd (using Bitwise AND)
n = 37
if n & 1:
    print(n, "is Odd")
else:
    print(n, "is Even")

print("\n" + "-"*50 + "\n")

# 3. Find whether a given number is power of 2 (using Bitwise)
m = 64
if m > 0 and (m & (m - 1)) == 0:
    print(m, "is a Power of 2")
else:
    print(m, "is NOT a Power of 2")

print("\n" + "-"*50 + "\n")

# 4. Admission Cutoff Check
score = 72
cutoff = 60
if score >= cutoff:
    print("Student Cleared the Exam ‚úÖ")
else:
    print("Student Did NOT Clear the Exam ‚ùå")

print("\n" + "-"*50 + "\n")

# 5. Check conditions on x with thresholds low, high
x = 50
low = 40
high = 60

print("x >= low:", x >= low)
print("x <= high:", x <= high)
print("x > high:", x > high)
print("x < low:", x < low)
print("x == low:", x == low)
print("x != high:", x != high)
